  <h2>Why DIY Tesla Repairs?</h2>

  <p>Here's the reality of Tesla ownership:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Service centers charge $150-200/hour</strong> — and appointments are often 2-4 weeks out</li>
    <li><strong>Many repairs are simple</strong> — Cabin filters, wipers, 12V batteries take minutes</li>
    <li><strong>Parts are widely available</strong> — OEM and aftermarket parts ship across the EU and US</li>
    <li><strong>Average savings: $200-2,000+ per repair</strong> by doing it yourself</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Makes Our Guides Different</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Written from the workshop floor</strong> — Not rewritten from forums or AI-generated fluff</li>
    <li><strong>Verified torque specs and procedures</strong> — Cross-checked against Tesla service manuals</li>
    <li><strong>Model year differences noted</strong> — Pre-2021, 2021-2023, 2024+ Highland variants covered separately</li>
    <li><strong>Honest difficulty ratings</strong> — We'll tell you when a job needs a professional</li>
    <li><strong>Real cost breakdowns</strong> — DIY vs. Tesla service vs. independent shop pricing</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Safety First</h2>

  <p><strong>If a repair is safety-critical or beyond your skill level, we'll say so.</strong> High-voltage battery work, structural repairs, and airbag systems should only be handled by trained professionals. Our guides focus on repairs that are safe and practical for home mechanics.</p>

